This category covers two topics: * [[History of music]] is the chronological description of music. * [[Music history]] is the academic study of the history of music.
{{Commons cat|Music history}}
[[Category:Fields of history|Music history]] [[Category:Musicology|History]] [[Category:Music|History]] [[Category:History by topic|Music history]] [[Category:Music genres|History]] [[Category:Cultural history|Music history]]

In music, '''eclecticism''' is the conscious use of styles alien to the [[composer]]'s own nature, or from a bygone era. The term is also used pejoratively to describe music whose composer, thought to be lacking originality, appears to have freely drawn on other models {{harv|Kennedy and Bourne|2006}}. This word can also be used to describe the music of composers who combine multiple styles, such as using a whole-tone variant of a pentatonic folksong over chromatic counterpoint, or a tertian arpeggiating melody over quartal or secundal harmonies. Eclecticism can also be through quotations, whether of a style (e.g., [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HjpZtBNzVKQ Shostakovich: Symphony No. 9]),{{Clarify|date=January 2015}}<!--What style is Shostakovich "quoting" in his Ninth Symphony?--> direct quotations of folksongs/variations of them (e.g., Mahler: Symphony No. 1; [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iBKd78WUa74 II] and [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RQCHgnpCGf4 III]) or direct quotations of other composers (e.g., Berio: [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9YU-V2C4ryU Sinfonia; III]) {{harv|Cope|1997|loc=230–33}}.

