{{catmain}}
{{commonscat|Traditional music}}
The term '''[[traditional music]]''' is often used as a broad classification of music genres that contrasts with '''[[classical music]]''' and '''[[popular music]]''' genres ''(see [[Musical genres]])'' as referring to genres founded neither upon any theoretical canon nor upon any mass commercial medium. The term has tended to replace '''[[folk music]]''', which has come to refer to European rural genres and contemporary American styles based upon these. The term '''[[ethnic music]]''', which gave rise to the discipline of [[ethnomusicology]], has also tended to give way to the term "traditional". Nevertheless it can be difficult to draw clear lines even between these few terms.<ref>Alison Latham (ed.) ''The Oxford Companion to Music'', OUP 2002, articles "The Classical era", "Folk music" and ''passim''.</ref> '''[[Indigenous music]]''' refers to the music of ethnic groups whose region has been occupied by later migrants: it has no strictly musical definition.

