{{refimprove|date=July 2013}}
'''Shaabi''' ({{lang-ar|شعبى}}'' {{transl|ar|ALA|Shaʻbī}}''&nbsp; {{IPA-arz|ˈʃæʕbi|pron}}) is an [[Egypt]]ian musical genre. It is a form of popular working-class music which evolved from [[baladi]] in the second half of the 20th century.
Shaabi literally means 'music of the people'. It originated in Cairo in the 1970s, as a new form of urban music expressing the difficulties and frustrations of modern Egyptian life.<ref name="Pop Culture Arab World!">{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Andrew|title=Pop Culture Arab World!|year=2005|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=1-85109-449-0}}</ref> Shaabi lyrics can be both intensely political, and filled with humour and double entendre. Because of its nature as street music, and a widespread indifference to copyright law among Egyptians, Shaabi today is mainly distributed on pirated tapes and CDs.
The first shaabi singer to rise to stardom was [[Ahmed Adaweyah]], whose first album in 1972 sold a million copies.<ref name="Pop Culture Arab World!" /> Like many shaabi singers, Adaweyah was famed for his [[mawwal]]. More recently, [[Shaaban Abdel Rahim]] rose to fame in 2000 with the controversial 'Ana Bakra Israel' ('I hate Israel'), and has remained something of a working-class hero due to a string of populist political hits.
Other well-known singers in the shaabi genre include [[Saad al-Soghayer]], [[Amina (Egyptian Singer)|Amina]], and [[Abdelbaset Hamouda]]. Another notable singer is [[Hakim (Egyptian singer)|Hakim]], who is from a middle-class background unlike most shaabi singers, and whose commercially successful brand of shaabi-pop is generally cheerful and apolitical.
== Electro Chaabi ==
The most recent new development to come out of Cairo's Shaabi scene is '[[mahraganat]]' ('festivals'; {{lang-ar|مهرجانات}}&nbsp; {{IPA-arz|mɑh.ɾɑ.ɡɑˈnɑːt|}}) music, also known as 'electro-shaabi'.<ref name="Out of Egypt’s Chaos, Musical Rebellion">{{cite news|last=Hubbard|first=Ben|title=Out of Egypt’s Chaos, Musical Rebellion|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/12/world/middleeast/egypts-chaos-stirs-musical-revolution.html|newspaper=New York TImes|date=11 May 2013}}</ref> The best-known artists in this genre are [[Oka Wi Ortega]],<ref>https://www.facebook.com/OkaWiOrtega</ref> Filo, Sadat, and Fifty. The genre was popularised in the by alternative culture magazine ''[[Audio Kultur]]'',<ref>http://audiokultur.com/electrochaabi/</ref> the ''[[Cairo Liberation Front]]'' and by the blog ''[[Generation Bass]]''.<ref>http://www.generationbass.com/2012/10/18/arabia-rising-egyptian-electro-chaabi/</ref>
