'''Latin music'''  ('''Música latina''' in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]) is a musical category encompassing music from Spanish-speaking areas anywhere around the world mainly from [[Latin America]] and [[Spain]].<ref name="morales">{{cite book|last1=Morales|first1=Ed|title=The Latin beat : The Rhythms and Roots of Latin music From Bossa Nova to Salsa and Beyond|date=2003|publisher=[[Da Capo Press]]|location=Cambridge, MA|isbn=0306810182|page=xiii|edition=1. Da Capo Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lpv25quOSnwC&lpg=PR13|accessdate=September 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name="stavans">{{cite book|last1=Stavans|first1=llan|authorlink=Ilan Stavans|title=Latin music : musicians, genres, and themes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qE-LBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PR18#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=2014|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|location=Santa Barbara, California:|isbn=9780313343964|page=xviii, 838|accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name="vivalatino">{{cite journal|last1=Lawrence|first1=Larry|last2=Wright|first2=Tom|title=¡Viva Latino!|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=January 26, 1985|volume=97|issue=4|pages=53, 62|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7CQEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PT109#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=April 9, 2015|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> Most definitions of Latin music also include Portuguese-language music from [[Brazil]] and sometimes [[Portugal]] as well.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Flores|first1=Juan|last2=Rosaldo|first2=Renato|title=A Companion to Latina/o Studies.|date=2007|publisher=Blackwell Pub.|location=Oxford|isbn= 9780470658260|page=50|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i3a1qVqHoJAC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA50#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=September 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Llewellyn|first1=Howell|title=ShowMarket To Focus On Development of Latin Music|journal=Billboard|date=November 25, 1995|volume=107|issue=47|page=72|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pw0EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&pg=PA72#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=July 30, 2015|publisher=Nielsen Media|issn=0006-2510}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Arenas|first1=Fernando|title=Lusophone Africa : Beyond Independence|date=2011|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=9780816669837|page=220|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eThbx7A_mEEC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA220#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=September 10, 2015}}</ref> The term, "Latin music", originates from the [[United States]] (US) due to the growing influence of [[Hispanic and Latino American]]s in the American music market beginning in the 1980s.<ref name="stavans"/><ref name="vivalatino"/> US trade industry groups<ref>{{cite web|last1=Edwards|first1=Bob|title=Profile: Latin Grammys at the Staples Center in Los Angeles|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-31750825.html|website=[[NPR]]|accessdate=August 7, 2015|date=September 13, 2000|subscription=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Barkley|first1=Elizabeth F.|title=Crossroads : the multicultural roots of America's popular music|date=2007|publisher=Pearson Prentice Hall|location=Upper Saddle River, NJ|isbn=9780131930735|page=232|edition=2.|quote=The U.S. record industry defines Latin music as simply any release with lyrics that are mostly in Spanish.}}</ref> such as [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) and [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] magazine define "Latin music" as any type of release with most of its lyrics in Spanish regardless of genre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/keystatistics.php?content_selector=research-about|title=About|website=Recording Industry Association of America|accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1099596/latin-sales-down-slightly-in-2011-digital-latin-sales-up|title=Latin Sales Down Slightly In 2011, Digital Latin Sales Up|last=Cobo|first=Leila|authorlink=Leila Cobo|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=January 5, 2012|accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Valdes-Rodriguez|first1=Alisa|title=The Loud and Quiet Explosions|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/dec/26/entertainment/ca-47489|accessdate=October 28, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Company|date=December 26, 1999}}</ref>

Major record labels such as [[Universal Music Group]], [[Sony Music]], and [[Warner Music]] have divisions which oversees acts from Latin America and the Iberian Peninsula with an executive that manages both regions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard's Latin Power Players List Revealed|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6648545/billboard-latin-power-players-list-2015?page=0%2C0|website=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=July 30, 2015|date=July 30, 2015}}</ref> Spain, Brazil, Mexico, and the United States are the largest Latin music markets in the world.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Llewellyn|first1=Howell|title=The Spanish Market Looks To Export Artists|journal=Billboard|date=November 11, 2000|volume=112|issue=46|page=78|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5RAEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA7&pg=PA78#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=April 9, 2015|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> In the 1990s, artists from Italy such as [[Eros Ramazzotti]], [[Laura Pausini]], and [[Tiziano Ferro]] successfully [[crossover (music)|crossed over]] to the Latin music field by recording Spanish-language versions of their songs.<ref name="stavans"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Obejas|first1=Achy|authorlink1=Achy Obejas|title=Italian Artists Conquer Latin Music Charts|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-04-04/news/9904040139_1_latin-music-eros-ramazzotti-italian|accessdate=January 4, 2015|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=April 4, 1999}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cobo|first1=Leila|title=Latin Notas|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=November 11, 2000|volume=112|issue=46|pages=47–48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5RAEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA7&pg=PA47#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=January 4, 2015|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> In 2000, the [[Latin Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences]] (LARAS) established the [[Latin Grammy Award]]s to recognize musicians who perform in Spanish or Portuguese.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/sep/12/news/ss-19479|title=One Little Word, Yet It Means So Much|last=Valdes-Rodriguez|first=Alisa|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Company|date=June 25, 1999|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref> Unlike the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]] (NARAS) which only accepts recordings that been released in the United States, LARAS admits any recordings in Spanish or Portuguese that have been released in Latin America, Spain, Portugal, and the United States.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Billboard Spotlights Spain & Portugal|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=November 20, 1999|volume=111|issue=47|page=91|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fwgEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=September 3, 2015|publisher=Nielsen N.V.|issn=0006-2510}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fernandez|first1=Enrique|title=After Birthing Pains, Latin Grammys Should Grow Strong|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2000-03-05/entertainment/0003031244_1_latin-music-latin-academy-latin-grammy-show|accessdate=July 31, 2015|work=Sun-Sentinel|publisher=McClatchy Company|date=March 5, 2000}}</ref> Similarly, the [[Latin Songwriters Hall of Fame]] was established in 2012 to recognize songwriters from Spanish- and Portuguese-speaking regions around the world.<ref name="miaminews">{{cite news|author1=S. Pajot|title=Latin Songwriters Hall of Fame Launches in Miami, Announces 2013 Nominees|url=http://blogs.miaminewtimes.com/crossfade/2012/12/latin_songwriters_hall_of_fame_2013_nominees.php|accessdate=October 30, 2014|work=[[Miami New Times]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|date=December 12, 2012}}</ref> In 2013, Spanish singer [[Julio Iglesias]] was recognized by the [[Guinness World Records]] as the best-selling male Latin artist of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2013/4/julio-iglesias-receives-world-record-certificate-in-beijing-47865/|title=Julio Iglesias receives world record certificate in Beijing|publisher=Guinness World Record|date=April 2, 2013|accessdate=December 24, 2013}}</ref>

