{{Infobox Sports league | title = Dew Tour | current_season = | logo = | pixels = | caption = | Formerly = AST Dew Tour | sport = [[Extreme sports]] | founded = 2005 | fame = | motto = | inaugural = | teams = | country = All | venue = | champion = | most_champs = | qualification = | folded = | website = [http://www.dewtour.com/ DewTour.com] | singles = | ceo = | Director = | TV = [[NBC Sports]] | related_comps = | Founder = }}
The '''Dew Tour''' is an [[extreme sports]] circuit organized by the [[Alli Sports]] division of [[NBC Sports Group]].
==History== {{expand section|early history|date=April 2016}}
The Dew Tour was originally formed as a joint venture between [[NBC Sports]] and [[Live Nation (events promoter)|Live Nation]]. In 2008, NBC sold a stake in the series to [[MTV Networks]], forming a new joint venture [[Alli Sports|Alli]] to manage the series, and broadcasting events on [[MTV2]]. Following the acquisition of [[NBC Universal]] by [[Comcast]], MTV sold its stake back to NBC in June 2011, with events being aired on [[NBCSN]] and [[Comcast SportsNet]] networks.<ref name=sbj-allimtv>{{cite web|title=NBC buys back Dew Tour stake from MTV|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2011/06/20/Media/Dew-Tour.aspx|publisher=Sports Business Journal|date=June 20, 2011|accessdate=March 9, 2012}}</ref><ref name=alli-nbc>{{cite web|title=NBC Sports moving action sports programming to Versus|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2011/11/14/Media/Dew-Tour.aspx|publisher=Sports Business Journal|date=November 14, 2011|accessdate=March 8, 2012}}</ref>
The first Winter Dew Tour, a spin-off focusing on [[winter sport]]s, was held in late-2008/early-2009 with events in [[snowboarding]] and [[freestyle skiing]].<ref name=gobreck>{{cite web |url=http://www.gobreck.com/press-releases/2008/november/12/worlds-top-athletes-shaun-white-hannah-teter-travis-rice-tanner-hall |title=World's Top Athletes Shaun White, Hannah Teter, Travis Rice, Tanner Hall and Sarah Burke Lead Impressive List of Athletes Competing on Winter Dew Tour |publisher=gobreck.com |date=2008-11-12 |accessdate=2014-02-13}}</ref>
In the 2012 season, the Dew Tour was reduced to three stops from seven; with two summer events in [[Ocean City, Maryland]] and [[San Francisco]], and a winter event in [[Breckenridge, Colorado]]; management argued that the increased saturation of extreme sports events made it harder to attract athletes to participate. Streetstyle and [[slopestyle]] events were also introduced in San Francisco and Breckenridge respectively. Although total attendance and television viewership was down for the season, the average attendance rose, and viewership of digital content also increased.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fewer equals better for Dew Tour|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2013/01/07/Events-and-Attractions/Dew-Tour.aspx|website=Sports Business Daily|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref>
In May 2013, the [[United States Ski and Snowboard Association]] reached an agreement with Alli to allow the Winter Dew Tour event in Breckenridge to serve as a qualifying event for the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] team. The arrangement gave the USSA control over certain aspects of the event, such as its format, and selling advertising to its own official sponsors during the telecast, and to promote its own Grand Prix series.<ref name=sbj-dewtourqualifier>{{cite web|title=Dew Tour to become Olympic qualifier|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2013/05/20/Olympics/Dew-Tour.aspx|work=Sports Business Journal|accessdate=15 July 2013}}</ref>
