==Opening ceremony==
Although the Games began on 2 July with table tennis events held in North Korea, the official opening ceremony was held on 18 August in Moscow, soon after the first events hosted by the Soviet Union started.<ref name=Games-open-with-challenge>{{cite news|last1=Schmemann |first1=Serge |date=19 August 1984|title=Friendship Games open with a Soviet challenge |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fpoRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QOgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2829,2815005}}</ref><ref name=open-with-pomp>{{cite news |date=19 August 1984 |title=Friendship Games open with pomp|newspaper=[[The Spokesman-Review]] |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=a_MRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9-4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3838,1743115 | location=[[Spokane]]}}</ref> The two-hour ceremony held at the [[Luzhniki Stadium|Central Lenin Stadium]]<ref name=open-with-pomp /> included "girls in white leotards [spinning] red and white beachballs in unison, (...) dozens of children in traditional costumes of the Soviet republics",<ref name=open-with-pomp /> a "squadron of young performers" which created "a human weaving machine by ducking and turning to mesh their colored banners"<ref name=open-with-pomp /> and "red-attired teenage girls with silver [[hula hoop]]s", which spelled the words 'USSR' and 'peace'.<ref name=open-with-pomp /> The ceremony was described as being "reminiscent of [[Olympic opening ceremony|Olympic galas]]".<ref name=open-with-pomp />

As in Olympic opening ceremonies,<ref name=open-with-pomp /> a torch bearer (Soviet runner and [[1980 Summer Olympics|1980]] gold medalist [[Viktor Markin]]) carried the flame into the stadium<ref name=open-with-pomp /> and lit a giant bowl which had been built for the 1980 Moscow Olympics.<ref name=Games-open-with-challenge /> The torch had been lit from an [[eternal flame]] for [[World War II]] victims located in the [[Kremlin]].<ref name=Games-open-with-challenge />

Teams marched onto the stadium behind flags, but unlike in the Olympics, they were not national teams but sporting organisations, such as [[Dynamo Sports Club|Dynamo]] or [[Spartak (sports society)|Spartak]].<ref name=Games-open-with-challenge />

Songs performed during the ceremony included a 1918 military march dedicated to the [[Red Army]], "Stadium of My Dreams", written for the 1980 Olympics,<ref name=who-is-coming>{{cite news|date=17 August 1984|title=Games open but just who is coming? |newspaper=[[The Spokesman-Review]] |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=afMRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9-4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6976,823056}}</ref> and a specially composed song with the chorus "To a sunny peace – yes, yes, yes / To a nuclear blast – no, no, no."<ref name=peace-dominating>{{cite news |last1=Eaton |first1=William |date=19 August 1984|title=Peace dominating message at Friendship Games opening|newspaper=[[The Daily Courier (Arizona)|The Daily Courier]] |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hPEKAAAAIBAJ&sjid=708DAAAAIBAJ&pg=2742,3591862 }}</ref><ref name=Games-open-with-challenge />

[[General Secretary of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union|General Secretary]] [[Konstantin Chernenko]] did not attend the ceremony<ref name=open-with-pomp /> as expected,<ref name=who-is-coming /> but five [[Politburo of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Politburo]] members were present: [[Dimitri Ustinov]], [[Mikhail Gorbachev]], [[Grigory Romanov]], [[Vitaly Vorotnikov]] and [[Viktor Grishin]].<ref name=open-with-pomp />

